'''Argenis Méndez''' (born Argenis Alexander Méndez Zapata; July 3, 1986 in [[San Juan de la Maguana]]) is a [[Dominican Republic|Dominican]] professional boxer best known for winning the silver medal at the junior world championships in 2004.

==Early Life and Amateur Career==
Argenis Mendez started boxing at the age of 12.<ref name =dibella>{{cite web|title=Argenis Mendez Bio|url=http://www.dbe1.com/node/123|publisher=Dibella Entertainment|accessdate=20 January 2012}}</ref>  Mendez won featherweight silver at the World Junior Championships 2004 where he beat Eddy Flores Cotilla but lost to Eduard Ambartsumyan, in the final.<ref name=mendez>{{cite web|title=Argenis Alexander MÉNDEZ ZAPATA|url=http://www.webcitation.org/5knIoZIj8|accessdate=20 January 2012}}</ref> 

He lost in the first round of the Olympics in 2004 against the Ukrainian, [[Maksym Tretyak]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espndeportes.espn.go.com/story?id=255742|title=El otro lado de la moneda|agency=EFE|publisher=ESPN Deportes|language=Spanish|date=2004-08-17|accessdate=2012-05-31}}</ref> Mendez qualified for the Olympic Games by ending up in first place at the [[2nd AIBA American 2004 Olympic Qualifying Tournament]] in [[Rio de Janeiro, Brazil]].<ref name=mendez />

In 2005, he beat [[Abner Cotto]] on his way to winning the PanAm Championships).<ref name=mendez /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.terra.com/espdep/articulo/html/fox201835.htm|title=Cubanos se quedaron con nueve de los once oros del Panamericano|agency=EFE|publisher=Terra|language=Spanish|date=2005-10-02|accessdate=2012-05-31}}</ref>

He also holds several wins over [[Carlos Velazquez]].<ref name=mendez />

Defeated Naskali Jyri Jarmo on points, 20-8 at the [[2005 World Amateur Boxing Championships]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://old.aiba.org/uploads/results/2005_World_Championships_Results_by_Day.pdf|title=XIII World Senior Boxing Championships|publisher=AIBA|date=2005-07-16|accessdate=2012-05-31}}</ref> but lost early against Russian amateur standout [[Aleksei Tishchenko]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://assets.usoc.org/assets/documents/attached_file/filename/2814/2005_Results.pdf|title=2005 Results|publisher=United States Olympic Committee|date=2005-07-17|accessdate=2012-05-31}}</ref> who had beaten him earlier in the year.<ref name=mendez />

==Professional career==
He debuted in 2006, knocking out Jose Fonseco in the second round at Santo Domingo in the Dominican Republic.<ref name=boxrec>{{cite web|title=Argenis Mendez|url=http://boxrec.com/list_bouts.php?human_id=378733&cat=boxer|accessdate=20 January 2012}}</ref> Achieving a 12 fight win streak, mainly at [[super featherweight]], until losing a close split decision to Jaime Sandoval, wherein he knocked down Sandoval in the first round.<ref name=dibella /> 

He came back to win 6 consecutive fight including 12-round decision victories over fringe contender Martin Honorio and former [[IBF]] super featherweight champion [[Cassius Baloyi]]. Mendez fought Honorio on May 8, 2010 in the [[Home Depot Center]] in [[Carson, California]], winning a close majority decision with scores, of 114-114,116-112, and 116-112. Honorio pressured Mendez using body attacks, while Mendez used his superior hand speed and combination punching to counter Honorio.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gabion|first=Ernest|title=Paul Williams Decisions Kermit Cintron, A Wild Ending|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/paul-williams-decisions-kermit-cintron-wild-ending--27623|accessdate=20 January 2012}}</ref> In an IBF super featherweight title eliminator, Mendez fought Baloyi in [[Brakpan]], [[Gauteng]], [[South Africa]] on January 29, 2011. Mendez won a unanimous decision victory, with scores of  117-110, 117-110, and 117-111, outclassing the former champion with his speed, and combination punching.<ref>{{cite web|last=Labate|first=Chris|title=Joyi-Takayama a No-Contest, Mendez Decisions Baloyi|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/joyi-takayama-no-contest-mendez-decisions-baloyi--35329|accessdate=20 January 2012}}</ref> 

Argenis Mendez finally got his chance for the vacant IBF super featherweight against former [[World Boxing Council]] super featherweight champion and [[Jorge Linares]] conqueror [[Juan Carlos Salgado]]. On September 10, 2011, at [[Zapopan]], [[Jalisco]], [[Mexico]], Mendez lost a close decision victory to Salgado. Both boxers landed good combination punches, and fought competitively. Mendez lost a point in the fifth round for hitting behind the head, but was able to drop Salgado in the final round.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rivera|first=Miguel|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/salgado-survives-argenis-mendez-wins-ibf-title--43633|title=Salgado Survives Argenis Mendez, wins the IBF Title}}</ref> 

He had a quick bounce-back victory over Alex Perez, on November 18, 2011 in [[Santo Domingo]], [[Dominican Republic]], winning a knockout in the second round.<ref>{{cite web|last=Woods|first=Michael|title=Agbeko out, so who's No. 1 on the NY P4P Top 5?|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/new-york/boxing/tag/_/name/argenis-mendez|accessdate=20 January 2012}}</ref>

In April 2012, Castillo signed for the [[boxing promoter]] Acquinity Sports alongside with compatriots [[Manuel Félix Díaz]] and [[Gilbert Lenin Castillo]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boxeomundial.net/boxeo.php?category=noticias&id=28336|title=Acquinity Sports firma a Lenin Castillo, Argenis Mendez y Felix Diaz|last=Sánchez|first=Reynaldo|newspaper=BoxeoMundial.net|date=2012-04-06|accessdate=2012-07-31}}</ref>

